body:
@rabbah @pritidesai The tricky thing is that we have well documented and supported the deployment of openwhisk under ubuntu and mac. Our ansible script has both of them covered. However, we have no support of openwhisk installation under windows. When ansible is deploying openwhisk under either mac or ubuntu, the CLI is built based on the OS openwhisk is running on, so either we build CLI locally for mac or ubuntu, which means there is a sort of no chance to build the windows CLI. This is basically how the current ansible for cli build works.

Anyhow, the deployment of openwhisk can be under mac or ubuntu, but the cli can be installed under another machine, when they are separate. However, our deployment of openwhisk put the openwhisk and cli on the same machine. That is why we do not have the chance to reach windows cli.

One approach to improve this can be the host machine, where cli will be installed, checks the OS, and pull the cli binary accordingly. I guess we can do the OS check in the ansible script, and download the binary based on the OS of the host machine.
